,"1637":"1637","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Conley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Down, Antrim, and Louth): shortened form of   Connolly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Connley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Conlee","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Coonley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Matha.","Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Connolly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Bridie, Seamus, Aidan, Dermot, Eamon, Patrick Joseph, Colm, Cormac, Declan, Eoin.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Conghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Conghal</i>’, a name meaning ‘hound valiant’, or of <b>Ó Conghalaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Conghalach</i>’, a derivative of <i>Conghal</i>; the two surnames have long been confused. Anglicized Irish forms Conneely, Connealy, Cunneely have arisen where loss of <i>gh</i> has caused lengthening of the second syllable of <i>Conghal</i>: they often also (Connacht) represent shortened forms of   McNeilly   from <i>Mac Conghaile</i>. Another possible origin is the West Cork name <b>Mac Coingheallaigh</b> (or <b>Ó Coingheallaigh</b>) ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Coingheallach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘faithful to pledges’. See   McNeilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":3,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":14,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":30,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":32,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":45,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Com